Docker Secrets — Feynman Style (Real-Time DevOps Explanation)

Think like this:

Imagine you built an application.

Your application needs:

database password
API token
AWS keys
SSL certificates

Now question:

Where will you store them?

If you put them directly inside:

Dockerfile
compose.yml
GitHub repo
environment variables

then anyone can see them.

That is dangerous in production.

What Docker Secrets Actually Do

Docker Secrets safely hide sensitive data and give it only to authorized containers.

Simple idea:

Secret stored securely
        ↓
Only required container can access it
        ↓
Nobody else can see it

So What We Do in Real Time

We create secrets separately.

Example:

echo "root123" | docker secret create mysql_password -

Now Docker stores password securely inside Swarm.

How Container Uses Secret

Docker mounts secret inside container:

/run/secrets/

Example:

/run/secrets/mysql_password

Application reads password from file.

Real-Time Compose File
version: '3.8'

services:
  backend:
    image: myapp

    secrets:
      - mysql_password

    environment:
      DB_PASSWORD_FILE: /run/secrets/mysql_password

secrets:
  mysql_password:
    external: true
